9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1174, L.D. 1756, “An Act to Establish
10 a Statewide Transportation Project Selection Prioritization Process”
11 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 1.
12 Amend the bill by striking out all of sections 3, 4 and 5 and inserting the following:
13 'Sec. 3. 23 MRSA §4209-B is enacted to read:
14 §4209-B. Transportation project selection prioritization
15 1. Transportation project selection prioritization process. The department and the
16 Maine Turnpike Authority shall develop and manage a statewide transportation project
17 selection prioritization process, referred to in this section as "the prioritization process."
18 The prioritization process must:
19 A. Be used for evaluation of projects administered in accordance with federal
20 transportation requirements and, in cooperation with municipalities, counties and other
21 planning organizations within the State, for funds allocated to the department and the
22 Maine Turnpike Authority;
23 B. Be used for the development of any plan for a project created by the department or
24 the Maine Turnpike Authority;
25 C. Take into consideration, at a minimum, highway, transit, rail, roadway, active
26 transportation and technology operations improvements and transportation demand
27 management strategies; and
28 D. Score and rank all proposed projects based on an objective and quantifiable analysis
29 factoring public input of projects proposed for funding using the State's key goals listed
30 in long-term transportation plans. Key goals include, but are not limited to:
31 (1) Safe travel with priority on avoiding crashes that cause death or serious injury
32 and protecting vulnerable users as defined in Title 29-A, section 101, subsection
33 91-A;
Page 1 - 132LR1653(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1174, L.D. 1756
1 (2) A well-managed transportation system measured by reliability and system
2 condition;
3 (3) A quality of life measured by economic impact analysis, including the health
4 of the State's downtowns and villages;
5 (4) Environmentally sustainable transportation systems measured by greenhouse
6 gas emissions from the transportation systems and effects on lands and waters,
7 including, but not limited to, storm water runoff and heat island effects; and
8 (5) Equitable access measured by consideration of access to jobs and essential
9 services, particularly for low-income households. Accessibility must be measured
10 using a peer-reviewed, data-informed tool.
11 2. Exclusions. The prioritization process may not apply to:
12 A. Projects in which funding is related to in-kind repair or replacement of existing
13 traffic control devices or asset management, including, but not limited to, bridge
14 rehabilitation, bridge-only bridge replacement projects, pavement repair or
15 replacement and guardrail repair or replacement; and
16 B. Projects that replace bicycle and pedestrian facilities, including, but not limited to,
17 sidewalks, shared-use paths or bicycle lanes. Projects under this paragraph must have
18 their designs upgraded from substandard to standard unless other funds are leveraged
19 for the bicycle and pedestrian components.
20 3. Report. The department and the Maine Turnpike Authority shall each submit a
21 report on the prioritization process, including a list of all scores and rankings of proposed
22 projects and how the weights of goals under subsection 1, paragraph D were applied, by
23 January 15th of each year to the Governor and the joint standing committee of the
24 Legislature having jurisdiction over transportation matters. The report must be made
25 publicly available on the department's publicly accessible website and the authority's
26 publicly accessible website.
27 4. Selection of projects. Beginning July 1, 2026, the department and the Maine
28 Turnpike Authority shall select projects for funding pursuant to subsection 1.
29 Sec. 4. Development of prioritization process. In developing the statewide
30 transportation project selection prioritization process under the Maine Revised Statutes,
31 Title 23, section 4209-B, the Department of Transportation and the Maine Turnpike
32 Authority must:
33 1. Weigh key goals under Title 23, section 4209-B, subsection 1, paragraph D for each
34 of the State's federally designated planning organization regions. For purposes of this
35 section, the prioritization process may assign different weights to each key goal, within
36 each region, based on the unique needs and characteristics of the region; and
37 2. Solicit input from municipalities, counties and other planning organizations, transit
38 operators, environmental groups, active transportation groups, economic development
39 groups and other stakeholders in the development of the prioritization process.
40 Sec. 5. Appropriations and allocations. The following appropriations and
41 allocations are made.
